{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586207"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:28:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:28:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15075"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15075"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0.07,0,0,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7763"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67784"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7763"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15075"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53249"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45498"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67784"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMicroscopic haematuria refers to the presence of red blood cells in the urine that is not visible to the naked eye and is detected through laboratory testing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the clinical significance of microscopic haematuria?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Persistent microscopic haematuria requires investigation in all cases","Transient microscopic haematuria requires urgent investigation","Testing should be delayed for six weeks if infection is present","Persistent haematuria requires two positive tests with infection present","Microscopic haematuria excludes episodes of visible haematuria"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Epersistent microscopic haematuria requires investigation in all cases\u003C/strong\u003E. This is because it may indicate significant underlying renal or urological pathology that requires diagnosis and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient microscopic haematuria requires urgent investigation\u003C/strong\u003E - Transient haematuria is common and often due to benign causes like exercise or menstruation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesting should be delayed for six weeks if infection is present\u003C/strong\u003E - Infection should be treated first, then urine should be retested to confirm if haematuria persists\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersistent haematuria requires two positive tests with infection present\u003C/strong\u003E - Persistent haematuria is defined as two positive tests at least six weeks apart in the absence of infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicroscopic haematuria excludes episodes of visible haematuria\u003C/strong\u003E - Patients with microscopic haematuria may also experience episodes of visible (macroscopic) haematuria\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPersistent microscopic haematuria is a significant finding that warrants appropriate investigation to identify or exclude underlying pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Persistent microscopic haematuria is defined as positive findings on two occasions at least six weeks apart in the absence of infection.","All cases of persistent microscopic haematuria require investigation to exclude significant pathology.","Transient microscopic haematuria is common and often benign."],"references":["Niemi MA, Cohen RA. Evaluation of microscopic hematuria: a critical review and proposed algorithm. Adv Chronic Kidney Dis. 2015 Jul;22(4):289-96. doi: 10.1053/j.ackd.2015.04.006. PMID: 26088073.","Leslie SW, Hamawy K, Saleem MO. Gross and Microscopic Hematuria. 2024 Feb 29. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30480952.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53249"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15075"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53249"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T22:43:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T22:44:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7763"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67784"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\u